<br>
1.  The game's overall challenge is much, much lower than Everquest.  There's much smaller penalties for death, no such thing as CR, experience can be easily regained using the /pray command, and you don't lose exp on death until level 6...and clerics get resurrection at level 10.  Anti-train code makes it certain that no more than three mobs can be aggro on you at any one time, and social aggro is coded so that a single player can pull one mob completely across a dungeon without any of its friends aggroing if done correctly.  It's also much more difficult to die accidentally, since you can't mistakenly attack members of your own realm.<br>
<br>
2.  Class balance is a total joke.  Clerics can slow, mez, heal, and many other things.  The desire to group relies much more on the way the exp system is coded.<br>
<br>
3.  These low challenge trends plus the group-for-more-exp system will quickly lead to a glut of level 30 players (the maximum PvE attainable level), all of whom have only one option at further advancement....Realm versus Realm combat.<br>
<br>
The problem with this is threefold.  First, a lot of people are going to be turned off by the idea of enforced PvP to advance.  Secondly, any system which uses wholly player-based combat as a system for advancement is guaranteed to be exploitable in one form or another...there's really, from what I've heard, very little to stop creative tactics from exploiting RvR solely for the purpose of advancement.  And, Thirdly, the aforementioned class balance issues.  While the rock-paper-scissors class system in DAoC works in theory (Archer owns Mage, Mage owns Tank, Tank owns Archer) how it works in execution is likely to be a very different story.<br>
<br>
Frankly, we'll all be buying Luclin when it comes out now, since we'll be getting another return on our investment of our level 60 characters with further advancement options, more PvE content, and better graphics, engine, and UI...what's the point of wasting two months puttering around in DAoC?<br>
<br>
